Definition 3.14 Let $\pi:Y\rightarrow X$ be a finite étale covering of constant degree $d$. By Proposition 3.13, $\mathcal{N}^{f}_{\pi}$ is uniquely determined as a monoidal functor up to a natural monoidal isomorphism, independently of the fpqc morphism $f$ trivializing $\pi$. We denote this functor simply by $\mathcal{N}_{\pi}$, and call it the norm functor for $\pi$.
Definition 6.5 Let $G$ be a finite group, and let $G^{\mathrm{op}}$ be its opposite group. For any Mackey functor $M=(M,\mathrm{res},\mathrm{cor},c)\in\mathrm{Mack}_{c}(G)$ $($in the notation of Remark 6.4$)$, we define its opposite Mackey functor $M^{\mathrm{op}}$ by $\displaystyle M^{\mathrm{op}}(H^{\mathrm{op}})$ $\displaystyle:=M(H)\qquad(H\leq G)$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{res}^{H^{\mathrm{op}}}_{K^{\mathrm{op}}}$ $\displaystyle:=\mathrm{res}^{H}_{K}\ \ \,\qquad(K\leq H\leq G)$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{cor}^{H^{\mathrm{op}}}_{K^{\mathrm{op}}}$ $\displaystyle:=\mathrm{cor}^{H}_{K}\ \ \qquad(K\leq H\leq G)$ $\displaystyle c_{g,H^{\mathrm{op}}}$ $\displaystyle:=c_{g^{-1},H}\ \qquad(g\in G,H\leq G).$ This gives an isomorphism of categories $\mathrm{op}:\mathrm{Mack}_{c}(G)\rightarrow\mathrm{Mack}_{c}(G^{\mathrm{op}}).$
