Definition 2.13. $\mathrm{SCG}$ is defined to be the 2-category whose 0-cells are symmetric categorical groups, 1-cells are monoidal functors, and 2-cells are monoidal transformations.
Definition 2.7. A symmetric categorical group $(\mathbb{G},\otimes,0)$ consists of (a1) a category $\mathbb{G}$ (a2) a tensor functor $\otimes:\mathbb{G}\times\mathbb{G}\rightarrow\mathbb{G}$ (a3) a unit object $0\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathbb{G)}$ (a4) natural isomorphisms $\displaystyle\alpha_{A,B,C}:A\otimes(B\otimes C)\rightarrow(A\otimes B)\otimes C,$ $\displaystyle\lambda_{A}:0\otimes A\rightarrow A,\ \rho_{A}:A\otimes 0% \rightarrow A,\ \gamma_{A,B}:A\otimes B\rightarrow B\otimes A$ which satisfy certain compatibility conditions $($cf. [5]$)$, and the following two conditions are satisfied: (b1) For any $A,B\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathbb{G)}$ and $f\in\mathbb{G}(A,B)$, there exists $g\in\mathbb{G}(B,A)$ such that $f\circ g=\mathrm{id}_{A}$, $g\circ f=\mathrm{id}_{B}$. (b2) For any $A\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathbb{G})$, there exist $A^{\ast}\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathbb{G})$ and $\eta_{A}\in\mathbb{G}(0,A\otimes A^{\ast})$.
